impersonate or kill. During the night, you should inspect players whose identities are uncertain (there is no need to check players who are highly suspected of being werewolves).\nWhen speaking during the day, your goal is to convince others that you are the real Seer. You must gather trust and\nshare your findings without exposing yourself too early. Even though revealing your identity might put you in danger,\na Seer trusted by both the Witch and the Guard can survive for at least three rounds if everyone acts accordingly.\nA good Seer will coordinate with the Witch and the Guard to divide responsibilities. For example, on the first night, the Guard protects the Seer, and the Witch doesn't use the antidote. On the second night, the Witch saves the Seer, and the Guard protects someone else.\n\n\nWitch Role Introduction:\nYou are the Witch. Each night, you will be told who has been attacked, and you must decide whether to use your antidote\nto save them or use your poison to eliminate another player. You only have one poison and one antidote, so use them wisely.\nDuring the daytime discussions, if the night ends without a death, you can reveal that you used your antidote to save someone, which may earn others' trust.\nTypically, you should use the antidote to save key players like the Seer, the Guard, or yourself, while the poison is best used to eliminate werewolves at night.\nHowever, be cautious: sometimes the werewolves will deliberately attack one of their own (self-knife strategy) to trick you into wasting the antidote, thereby boosting their credibility.\n\n\nGuard Role Introduction:\nYou are the Guard. Each night, you can choose one player to protect from being killed by the werewolves. You cannot protect\nthe same player two nights in a row. Your role is critical in keeping important players like the Seer or the Witch alive.\nYou are in a constant mental battle with the werewolves, trying to predict who they will target. It might not always be the Seer, as the werewolves might expect you to protect them and kill someone else. In general, you should avoid revealing your identity unless absolutely necessary.\n\n\n\n\nYou are Edna, your role in this game is guard.\nWerewolf game starting. Initializing day-night cycle.\nSYSTEM: Starting day-night cycle for Day 1\nSYSTEM: Night 1 begins. Werewolves and special roles take actions.\nGuard action processed. Sylvia is protected this night.\nGuard has chosen to protect a player.\nWerewolves have chosen their target.\nSeer has checked a player's identity.\nWitch has made her decision on potion use.\nSYSTEM: Day 1 begins. Players discuss and vote on potential suspects.\nSheriff election candidates: Jason\nJason's speech: Good morning, everyone. My name is Jason, and I am running for sheriff today. I have been a part of this village for a while now, and I have always been committed to its survival. I believe that as sheriff, I can help us work together more effectively to identify and eliminate the werewolves among us.\n\nFirst and foremost, I want to emphasize that I am here to listen. I understand that everyone has their own perspective and concerns, and I believe that by working together, we can make better decisions. As sheriff, I will strive to create an environment where everyone feels heard and valued.\n\nIf elected, my plan is to focus on communication and trust-building. I believe that by fostering a sense of community, we can better identify suspicious behavior and work together to protect our village. I will also be open to suggestions and ideas from others, as I believe that the strength of our village lies in our collective wisdom.\n\nThank you for considering my candidacy. I look forward to working with you all to ensure the safety and prosperity of our village.\nJason has been elected as the sheriff.\nSheriff election votes:\nSylvia voted for Jason\nEdna voted for Jason\nLisette voted for Jason\nKenneth voted for Jason\nAmee voted for Jason\nRandy voted for Jason\nRobert voted for abstain\nMegan voted for Jason\n(Note: The voting order reflects only the system's query sequence and does not imply any strategic alignment or motive.)\nNo players deceased during the night.\nNo players deceased during the night.\nThe speaking sequence for this round is: Kenneth, Lisette, Megan, Randy, Robert, Sylvia, Amee, Edna, Jason\nKenneth's speech: Thank you, Jason, for your inspiring speech. I completely agree with your emphasis on communication and trust-building. It's crucial that we work together as a village to identify and eliminate the werewolves without jumping to conclusions. I believe that by fostering a sense of community and mutual respect, we can better identify suspicious behavior and protect our village. Let's all contribute our ideas and insights to make informed decisions. I'm here to help in any way I can, and I look forward to working with you all to ensure the safety and prosperity of our village.\nLisette's speech: Thank you, Jason and Kenneth, for your inspiring speeches. I completely agree with the importance of communication and trust in our village. It's crucial that we work together to identify and eliminate the werewolves without jumping to conclusions. I want to reassure everyone that the night was peaceful, and no one was attacked. This suggests that the werewolves may be targeting someone specific or that we might be on the right track with our strategy. Let's continue to gather more information and work together to protect our village. We should be cautious and not rush into accusations, as that could lead to mistakes. By staying united and focused, I believe we can identify the werewolves and ensure the safety of our village.\nMegan's speech: Thank you, Jason and Kenneth, for your inspiring speeches. I completely agree with the importance of communication and trust in our village. It's crucial that we work together to identify and eliminate the werewolves without jumping to conclusions. I want to add that the ni